</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pine woodland from 1500 to 2000 m. Endemic to Oaxaca.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">MEXICO. Oaxaca</emphasis>
: Abasolo, Santa 
<taxonomicName authority="Buenavista, A. Saynes" authorityName="Buenavista, A. Saynes" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rosa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
Rosa Buenavista, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. Saynes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
627 (IEB); San Felipe Tejalapa, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. Cruz</emphasis>
133 (IEB).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Resembling 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="crinicalyx">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea crinicalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allies in the fleshy spines on the calyx but the long thick pedicels are somewhat reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="setosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. setosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The solitary flowers and ovate, cordate, glabrous, spineless leaves render this species very distinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
